            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Ahoy, matey! Arr! Before I set ye up proper — what port (city or zip) be ye in? If ye tell me, I’ll fetch the weather and give a tailored outfit for today.\n\nMeanwhile, here be some quick, sea-tested outfit rules depending on the weather ye might be facin’:\n\n- Scorchin’ sun (hot: >27°C / >80°F): Wear light, breathable fabrics (cotton or linen), short sleeves or a sundress, shorts, sandals or breathable sneakers. Don a wide-brim hat, sunglasses, and slather on sunscreen. Carry a water bottle, yarrr.\n\n- Warm / mild (18–27°C / 65–80°F): Lightweight layers — short-sleeve shirt with a light cardigan or unlined jacket ye can tie 'round yer waist. Comfortable pants or shorts and sneakers.\n\n- Cool (10–18°C / 50–65°F): Long-sleeve shirt or sweater plus a light-to-medium jacket. Jeans or chinos and closed shoes. A scarf can be handy if the wind picks up.\n\n- Chilly / breezy (0–10°C / 32–50°F): Warm jacket, sweater or fleece, long pants, boots or insulated shoes, and a hat. Layer up so ye can shed or add as needed.\n\n- Cold / freezing (<0°C / <32°F): Heavy coat, thermal layers, hat, gloves, warm boots, and a scarf to keep ye from gettin’ frostbite like a scurvy deckhand.\n\n- Rainy or wet: Waterproof jacket or raincoat, umbrella, quick-dry fabrics, and water-resistant shoes or boots. Keep valuables in a waterproof bag.\n\nIf ye tell me yer location and what ye’ll be doin’ (work, walk, hike, go to a party), I’ll give ye a spot-on outfit fit for a captain. Arr!",
